name: Box
description: Add a Box Instance to connect your existing Box account to the Cloud Storage and Documents Hub, allowing you to manage files and folders. You will need your Box account information to add an instance.
configDescription: If you do not have an Box.net account, you can create one at Box.Net Signup

configuration.name: Event poller stream position
configuration.description: Used to determine the last position to poll from

configuration.name: Base URL
configuration.description: The Base URL to make API requests to this endpoint

configuration.name: Allow Select Fields parameter
configuration.description: Enables use of global fields query parameter to filter response to only specified fields. This will override any existing vendor functionality on the connector

configuration.name: Document Hub Tagging
configuration.description: Enable Tagging of Documents. Paths and Tags will be stored in CE database in Clear Text

configuration.name: Event Notification Subscription ID
configuration.description: The subscription ID for the webhook events subscription

configuration.name: Filter null values from the response
configuration.description: Used to enable/disable filtering of null values from the responses

configuration.name: Default select fields
configuration.description: Generic map used to specify default fields for bulk download and GET /all requests. Each key should be the canonical objectName and values may be specified as a comma-delimited string or a list of strings

configuration.name: Authentication Type
configuration.description: Select oauth2 or jwtOauth the process through which needs to provision an instance

configuration.name: JWT Issuer
configuration.description: JWt Issuer - The Issuer of JWT Base64 Encoded Key

configuration.name: Vendor Event Type
configuration.description: Select the type for receiving events from box

configuration.name: Event poller refresh interval
configuration.description: Used to determine how often to poll the application (in minutes)

configuration.name: Event Poller Resources Configuration
configuration.description: Event Poller Resources Configuration. The configuration is defined via JSON, an example of which is as follows - { "documents": { "url": "/hubs/docuemnts/documents"} }

configuration.name: Event Notification Callback URL
configuration.description: An application callback URL used for event notifications from Box via Cloud Elements, e.g., Updated Files, Created Folders, etc.

configuration.name: Callback Notification Signature Key
configuration.description: A key used to generate a validation hash header of the event/bulk notification webhook callback payload

resources.description: Copies a file specified by a file path to another file path, leaving the original intact. If the source file path does not exist an error response is returned. If the destination path includes directories that do not exist, they will be created. Copying a file that already exists results in an error response unless `overwrite` is set to `true`

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The full path to the file (e.g. /myDirectory/myFile.txt)

parameters.name: overwrite
parameters.description: On optional flag indicating if the destination file should overwritten, if one already exists at the destination path. If this parameter is omitted or set to false, and the destination file already exists, then the file will not be overwritten and an error will be returned. Defaults to false

parameters.name: body
parameters.description: A CloudFile object representing the destination file. Path is required and no other fields are supported

filesCustomFieldsListObject.description: Returns all of the metadata instances associated with the file.

$id.description: 36-character UUID to identify the metadata object

$parent.description: The ID of the object the metadata object belongs to. Both file and folder objects are supported. Updating metadata does not directly affect the parent object, such as changing the modified_at field for a file or folder.

$scope.description: The scope of the object. global and enterprise scopes are supported. The global scope contains the properties template, while the enterprise scope pertains to custom templates within the enterprise. The ID of the enterprise will be appended to the enterprise scope in this format: enterprise_{id}

$template.description: The key of the template. Together with $parent and $scope, this forms a unique identifier for the metadata instance.

$type.description: A unique identifier for the 'type' of this instance. This is an internal system property and should not be used by a client application.

$typeVersion.description: The last-known version of the template of the object. This is an internal system property and should not be used by a client application.

$version.description: The version of the metadata object. Starts at 0 and increases every time a user-defined property is modified.

keys.description: Custom value(s) defined by the template. These values also have a corresponding display name that are viewable in applications like the Box web application. The total size of a template instance can not exceed 16384 characters. Since the '$' character is reserved for metadata service keys, custom values can not be prefixed with the '$' character.

customFieldsPatch.description: Update a metadata instance on a file.

$id.description: 36-character UUID to identify the metadata object

from.description: Required for move or copy. The path that designates the source key, in the format of a JSON-Pointer, formatted in the same way as path. Used in conjunction with path: from specifies the source, path specifies the destination.

path.description: he path that designates the key, in the format of a JSON-Pointer. Since all keys are located at the root of the metadata instance, the key must be prefixed with a /. Special characters ~ and / in the key must be escaped according to JSON-Pointer specification. The value at the path must exist for the operation to be successful.

scope.description: The scope of the metadata object (global or enterprise_{enterprise_id})

template.description: The key of the template. For example, the global scope has the properties template.

value.description: The value to be set or tested. Required for add, replace, and test operations. For add, if value already exists, then previous value will be overwritten by the new value. For replace, the metadata value must exist before replacing.For test, the value of the existing metadata instance must match the specified value.

access.description: The access level specified when the shared link was created. Can be open ('People with the link'), company ('People in your company'), or collaborators ('People in this folder'). resources.description: Returns a list of all groups

groupsListObject.description: Returns all of the groups for given enterprise. Must have permissions to see an enterprise's groups.

created_at.description: When the group object was created

description.description: Human readable description of the group. This can be up to 255 characters long. Needs to be accessed via the fields parameter.

external_sync_identifier.description: An arbitrary identifier that can be used by external group sync tools to link this Box Group to an external group. Example values of this field could be an Active Directory Object ID or a Google Group ID. We recommend use of this field in order to avoid issues when group names are updated in either Box or external systems. Needs to be accessed via the fields parameter.

id.description: The ID of the group object

invitability_level.description: Specifies who can invite the group to collaborate on folders (Create Collaboration). admins_only Master Admin, Co-admins, the group Group Admin. admins_and_members Admins listed above and group members. All_managed_users All managed users in the enterprise.

member_viewability_level.description: Specifies who can view the members of the group (Get Memberships for Group). Admins_only Master Admin, Coadmins, group Group Admin. admins_and_members Admins and group members. All_managed_users All managed users in the enterprise.

modified_at.description: When the group object was last modified

provenance.description: Keeps track of which external source this group is coming from . This should be a human-readable identifier up to 255 characters long. Setting this will also prevent Box users from editing the group name and its members directly via the Box web application. This is desirable for one-way syncing of groups. Needs to be accessed via the fields parameter.

Performs a text search of file names and directory names.  The content of files is not searched.  The search uses substring matching so searching for "exam" will match on "example.txt".  Subdirectories are also searched.  The search returns a list of CloudFiles that match search parameters

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The full path to the folder to start searching from (e.g. /myDirectory)

parameters.name: text
parameters.description: Text in the file or folder name

parameters.name: startDate
parameters.description: The start date (based on the created date of the file or folder) if used, end date is required

parameters.name: endDate
parameters.description: The end date (based on the created date of the file or folder) if used, start date is required

parameters.name: tags[]
parameters.description: Any tags associated with the files (not applicable to folders)

parameters.name: pageSize
parameters.description: The page size for pagination, which defaults to 200 if not supplied

parameters.name: page
parameters.description: The start page for pagination, which defaults to 1 if not supplied

parameters.name: where
parameters.description: The CEQL search expression, or the where clause, without the WHERE keyword, in a typical SQL query. Available search parameters are path, text, startDate, endDate, & tags. Users can also leverage Box metadata template filtering by specifying the templateKey, scope, & fields to filter by appending `template_` to `templateKey`, `scope`, and the field name(s) (e.g. `template_fieldName = 'fieldValue'`). Tags can be searched using the IN operator - e.g. `tags IN ('tagName1','tagName2',..)`. Example query - `text = 'sample' AND startDate = '2016-12-01T00:00:00.000Z'`
